    {
      "id": "def:inference-handle",
      "name": "\\(\\widehat C_n,\\widehat C_n^\\xi,\\widehat c_{1-\\alpha},\\widehat{\\mathcal K}_{n,1-\\alpha}\\)",
      "construction": "Use a normalized tensor-product spline or compactly supported wavelet basis \\(p_K(x)\\) of order at least \\(\\lceil\\beta\\rceil\\), with \\(K=K_n\\), and fixed \\(J\\)-folds. On training complements fit truncated series logits \\(\\widehat\\pi^{(-j)},\\widehat e_k^{(-j)}\\) and bounded series least squares \\(\\widehat\\mu_{sk}^{(-j)}\\). Require for this construction \\(K_n\\log n/n=o(1)\\), \\(K_n^{-\\beta/d}=o(n^{-1/4})\\), foldwise uniform errors \\(r_{\\pi,n},r_{e,n},r_{\\mu,n}\\), and \\(r_{\\mu,n}(r_{e,n}+r_{\\pi,n})=o(n^{-1/2})\\). Put \\(p_s(x)=\\pi(x)^s[1-\\pi(x)]^{1-s}\\), \\(R^\\mu_{sk}=1\\{S=s,A=k\\}[Y-\\mu_{sk}(X)]/[p_s(X)e_k(X,s)]\\), and \\(R^e_{sk}=1\\{S=s\\}[1\\{A=k\\}-e_k(X,s)]/p_s(X)\\). For any face \\(h\\in\\{V_t^-,V_t^+,W_t^-,W_t^+\\}\\), define \\(\\psi_h(O;\\theta)=h(X;\\theta)-E_Ph(X;\\theta)+\\sum_{s,k}\\partial_{\\mu_{sk}}h(X;\\theta)R^\\mu_{sk}+\\sum_{s,k}\\partial_{e_k(\\cdot,s)}h(X;\\theta)R^e_{sk}\\), with branchwise directional derivatives of the displayed clipped formula; the \\(\\pi\\)-derivative is zero. Let \\(\\mathcal S_n^{\\mathrm{act}}\\) collect centered face scores attaining a lower maximum, upper minimum, positive-part contact, or outer arm maximum at every \\(\\theta\\in\\Theta_n\\), retaining all ties. Its sufficient performance conditions are an envelope \\(F\\) with \\(\\sup_{P\\in\\overline{\\mathcal P}}E_PF^q<\\infty\\) for some \\(q>4\\), \\(\\log N(\\eta,\\mathcal S_n^{\\mathrm{act}},L_2(P))\\le v\\log(A_0/\\eta)\\) uniformly in \\(P\\) and \\(0<\\eta\\le1\\), and a fixed studentization floor for nonzero-variance scores; zero-variance scores are deterministically zero. Let \\(\\widehat C_n(\\theta)\\) be the cross-fitted empirical face vector passed through the lower-max, upper-min, positive-part, expectation, and outer-max map \\(\\mathfrak F\\). With independent mean-zero unit-variance multipliers, put \\(\\mathbb G_n^\\xi=n^{-1/2}\\sum_i\\xi_i\\widehat\\psi_i\\), choose \\(\\delta_n\\downarrow0\\) with \\(n^{-1/2}/\\delta_n\\to0\\) and \\((r_{\\pi,n}+r_{e,n}+r_{\\mu,n})/\\delta_n\\to0\\), and set \\(\\widehat C_n^\\xi=[\\mathfrak F(\\widehat\\eta_n+\\delta_n\\mathbb G_n^\\xi)-\\mathfrak F(\\widehat\\eta_n)]/\\delta_n\\). Take deterministic \\(\\Theta_n\\subset[0,1]^2\\) with mesh \\(h_n\\to0\\) and interpolation error \\(o(n^{-1/2})\\). Let \\(\\widehat c_{1-\\alpha}\\) be the conditional \\((1-\\alpha)\\)-quantile of \\(\\sup_{\\theta\\in\\Theta_n}\\widehat C_n^\\xi(\\theta)\\), and define \\(\\widehat{\\mathcal K}_{n,1-\\alpha}=\\{\\theta\\in\\Theta_n:\\sqrt n\\widehat C_n(\\theta)\\le\\widehat c_{1-\\alpha}\\}\\), enlarged by measurable closed grid cells in \\(\\Theta\\). Hong--Li supplies the finite-difference derivative, Fang--Santos the directional map, Chernozhukov--Lee--Rosen contact selection, and cross-fitting nuisance linearization.",
      "inputs": [
        "\\(O_i=(X_i,S_i,A_i,Y_i)\\)",
        "\\(J,\\mathcal I_j,p_K,K_n\\)",
        "\\(\\widehat\\eta^{(-j)},\\widehat\\pi^{(-j)},\\widehat e_t^{(-j)},\\widehat\\mu_{st}^{(-j)}\\)",
        "\\(p_s,R^\\mu_{sk},R^e_{sk},\\psi_h,\\mathcal S_n^{\\mathrm{act}}\\)",
        "\\(\\xi_i,\\mathbb G_n^\\xi,\\delta_n,\\Theta_n,h_n\\)",
        "\\(\\varepsilon,\\alpha\\)"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "statements": [
    {
      "id": "lem:observational-mixture-identity",
      "kind": "lemma",
      "statement": "Every \\(Q\\) satisfying \\(\\textup{ass:pushforward}\\) obeys \\(q_{t0}(X)=e_t(X,0)\\mu_{0t}(X)+e_{1-t}(X,0)c_t(X)\\) \\(P_X\\)-almost surely for each \\(t\\in\\mathcal T\\). Conditioning \\(E_Q[Y(t)\\mid X,S=0]\\) on \\(A\\), the pushforward identifies the weights with \\(e_k\\), its realized-outcome coordinate identifies the \\(A=t\\) conditional mean with \\(\\mu_{0t}\\), and the other conditional mean is \\(c_t\\).",
      "depends_on": [
        "ass:pushforward"
      ],
      "status": "to-prove",
      "justification": "The observational mixture is a consequence of an observed extension, rather than an additional restriction.",
      "gap": "The sensitivity restrictions need a law-level bridge from the missing-arm mean to observed conditional means.",
      "consumer": "It maps the NUC interval for \\(c_t\\) into \\([W_t^-,W_t^+]\\)."
    },
    {
      "id": "prop:positive-violation-infeasibility",
      "kind": "proposition",
      "statement": "Under \\(\\textup{ass:uniform-treatment-positivity}\\), \\(C_P(\\theta)>0\\) implies \\(\\mathcal M(P,\\rho,\\gamma)=\\varnothing\\). Indeed, any \\(Q\\in\\mathcal M(P,\\rho,\\gamma)\\) has \\(c_t\\in[C_t^-,C_t^+]\\); Lemma 1 then gives \\(q_{t0}\\in[W_t^-,W_t^+]\\), while study exchangeability gives \\(q_{t0}\\in[V_t^-,V_t^+]\\). Thus every nonnegative conditional violation is zero almost surely.",
      "depends_on": [
        "ass:pushforward",
        "ass:relative-nuc",
        "ass:study-exchangeability",
        "ass:uniform-treatment-positivity",
        "lem:observational-mixture-identity",
        "def:exact-endpoints",
        "def:compatibility-functional",
        "def:latent-class"
      ],
      "status": "to-prove",
      "justification": "This proved necessity direction turns a positive no-cancellation functional into a certificate of infeasibility.",
      "gap": "It distinguishes an interval-restriction consequence from the unresolved common-extension converse.",
      "consumer": "It certifies incompatibility without relying on the signed proxy."
    },
    {
      "id": "oeq:exact-compatibility",
      "kind": "openendedquestion",
      "statement": "Conjecture 1. Under \\(\\textup{ass:standard-borel}\\), \\(\\textup{ass:uniform-study-positivity}\\), and \\(\\textup{ass:uniform-treatment-positivity}\\), is \\(\\mathcal M(P,\\rho,\\gamma)\\ne\\varnothing\\) if and only if \\(C_P(\\theta)=0\\)? The handle is the measurable-selector construction: select \\(q_t^\\star\\) from each clipped intersection, recover \\(c_t^\\star\\), copy trial kernels under joint randomization, and conditionally independently couple endpoint-kernel missing potentials in study zero.",
      "depends_on": [
        "ass:standard-borel",
        "ass:pushforward",
        "ass:trial-randomization",
        "ass:relative-nuc",
        "ass:study-exchangeability",
        "ass:uniform-study-positivity",
        "ass:uniform-treatment-positivity",
        "lem:observational-mixture-identity",
        "prop:positive-violation-infeasibility",
        "def:exact-endpoints",
        "def:compatibility-functional",
        "def:endpoint-kernel",
        "def:selector-extension-handle",
        "def:latent-class"
      ],
      "status": "to-prove",
      "justification": "Two sensitivity restrictions are interpretable only if one joint support-respecting causal law can satisfy both.",
      "gap": "Lanners et al. give pointwise interval inequalities. Yu et al. already combine randomized and non-randomized studies with two internal/external-bias sensitivity parameters. The open advance is the exact observed-law common-latent-extension characterization of the support-clipped Lanners restrictions, with a mixture identity, measurable selectors, and one explicit joint extension; the zero-set test refines only the practical signed proxy.",
      "consumer": "A proof characterizes the sensitivity pairs that can support a causal data-fusion bound."
    },
    {
      "id": "prop:two-stratum-cancellation",
      "kind": "proposition",
      "statement": "For \\(P^{\\mathrm{can}}\\) at \\(\\theta=(1,1)\\), all means lie in \\([1/4,8]\\), \\(\\pi(x_j)=e_t(x_j,s)=1/2\\), and all observed kernels are valid. For arm \\(0\\), the published un-clipped intervals are \\([0,1]\\) and \\([2,6]\\) at \\(x_1\\), giving \\(H_0^{\\mathrm{LRVP}}(x_1)=-1\\), and \\([0,8]\\) and \\([2,6]\\) at \\(x_2\\), giving \\(H_0^{\\mathrm{LRVP}}(x_2)=4\\). Hence \\(G_0^{\\mathrm{LRVP}}=(4/5)(-1)+(1/5)4=0\\). For arm \\(1\\), the published intervals are \\([0,2]\\) and \\([1/2,3/2]\\) at both strata, so \\(H_1^{\\mathrm{LRVP}}=G_1^{\\mathrm{LRVP}}=1\\). The support-clipped arm-zero intervals are \\(V_0=[1/4,1]\\), \\(C_0=[1/4,8]\\), and \\(W_0=[17/8,6]\\) at \\(x_1\\), and \\(V_0=[1/4,8]\\), \\(C_0=[1/4,8]\\), and \\(W_0=[17/8,6]\\) at \\(x_2\\). For arm \\(1\\), they are \\(V_1=[1/4,2]\\), \\(C_1=[1/4,2]\\), and \\(W_1=[5/8,3/2]\\) at both strata. Thus the only conditional violation is \\(9/8\\) at \\(x_1\\) for arm \\(0\\), so \\(C_{P^{\\mathrm{can}}}(1,1)=9/10\\) and \\(\\mathcal M(P^{\\mathrm{can}},1,1)=\\varnothing\\) by Proposition 1.",
      "depends_on": [
        "def:published-endpoints",
        "def:exact-endpoints",
        "def:compatibility-functional",
        "def:two-stratum-witness",
        "prop:positive-violation-infeasibility"
      ],
      "status": "to-prove",
      "justification": "The finite law exhibits cross-stratum cancellation in the practical signed-average proxy.",
      "gap": "Lanners et al. use the signed expectation operationally in Appendix D/E.3; this calculation shows it can accept despite a proved incompatibility certificate.",
      "consumer": "It is a reproducible stress test for Project STAR-style compatibility maps."
    },
    {
      "id": "lem:zero-sensitivity-reduction",
      "kind": "lemma",
      "statement": "At \\(\\theta=(0,0)\\), \\((0,0)\\in\\mathcal K(P)\\) if and only if \\(\\mu_{0t}(X)=\\mu_{1t}(X)\\) \\(P_X\\)-almost surely for every \\(t\\in\\mathcal T\\).",
      "depends_on": [
        "def:exact-endpoints",
        "def:compatibility-functional"
      ],
      "status": "to-prove",
      "justification": "The zero-sensitivity corner has an algebraic reduction to conditional mean exchangeability.",
      "gap": "This is a sanity check rather than an independent novelty claim.",
      "consumer": "It checks implementations of the observed-law functional."
    },
    {
      "id": "oeq:uniform-contact-inference",
      "kind": "openendedquestion",
      "statement": "Under \\(P\\in\\overline{\\mathcal P}\\), \\(\\textup{ass:iid}\\), and the construction-performance conditions in \\(\\textup{def:inference-handle}\\), can the numerical directional-delta contact-set multiplier procedure attain \\(\\liminf_{n\\to\\infty}\\inf_{P\\in\\overline{\\mathcal P}}P(\\mathcal K(P)\\subseteq\\widehat{\\mathcal K}_{n,1-\\alpha})\\ge1-\\alpha\\) and uniformly level-\\(\\alpha\\) tests of \\(C_P(\\theta)=0\\), including positive-\\(P_X\\)-mass endpoint and arm ties? For sequences \\(P_n\\in\\overline{\\mathcal P}\\), what are the regular local separation rate and local power as \\(C_{P_n}(\\theta)\\to0\\)?",
      "depends_on": [
        "ass:iid",
        "def:compatibility-functional",
        "def:primitive-class",
        "def:inference-handle"
      ],
      "status": "to-prove",
      "justification": "Ties make the learned max-min-positive-part functional directionally, not ordinarily, smooth.",
      "gap": "Hong--Li and Fang--Santos supply numerical and directional bootstrap ingredients, Chernozhukov--Lee--Rosen supplies contact selection, and cross-fitting supplies nuisance linearization; none proves the stated uniform tie-inclusive learned-nuisance coverage, testing, and local-power result for this two-study zero set.",
      "consumer": "Valid outer confidence regions separate sampling uncertainty from genuine joint incompatibility."
    }
  ],
  "sampling_model": {
    "design": "Independent draws from the observed two-study law \\(P\\).",
    "units": "\\(O_i=(X_i,S_i,A_i,Y_i)\\) for \\(i=1,\\ldots,n\\).",
    "treatment": "The latent class imposes joint conditional randomization in study one.",
    "overlap": "Study and within-study treatment propensities are bounded by \\(\\varepsilon\\).",
    "nuisance_estimation": "The declared cross-fitted series learners enter the explicit face-score construction."
