  "tldr": "The proposal studies the observed-law compatibility region for the published linear sensitivity model on \\([0,1]^2\\). Lanners et al. derive pointwise interval requirements and use a signed-average proxy operationally. Yu et al. already combine randomized and non-randomized studies using triplet matching and two internal/external-bias sensitivity parameters; the narrower question here is whether the corrected Lanners restrictions admit one support-respecting common latent causal law. A proved no-cancellation infeasibility implication and a fully specified two-stratum law show that the proxy can cancel across strata. Conjecture 1 asks whether zero conditional violation is also sufficient for one support-respecting common latent extension; Open-ended Question 2 asks for tie-inclusive learned-nuisance inference.",
  "project_justification": {
    "gap": "Lanners et al. impose pointwise interval inequalities for feasibility and use a signed expectation as a practical proxy; their resampling fixes fitted nuisance functions. Yu et al. already use triplet matching and two internal/external-bias sensitivity parameters to combine randomized and non-randomized studies.",
    "niche": "The niche is not two-parameter sensitivity analysis or combining study types: it is whether the particular support-clipped Lanners restrictions are jointly realizable by one support-respecting latent causal law, and how to infer the resulting no-cancellation zero set with learned nuisances and ties.",
    "fill": "The proposal supplies a proved no-cancellation infeasibility certificate, a cancellation counterexample to the signed proxy, a selector-based common-extension conjecture, and a numerical-delta inference question for that compatibility zero set."
  },
  "related_work": "Lanners, Rudin, Volfovsky, and Parikh, Section 4, Lemma 1, Theorem 1, and Remark 1 impose pointwise population interval inequalities, while Appendix D/E.3 uses \\(G_t^{\\mathrm{LRVP}}\\) as a practical signed-expectation proxy. Conjecture 1 concerns an exact common-latent-extension characterization, and Proposition 2 shows cross-stratum cancellation in that proxy. Yu, Karmakar, Vandeleest, and Schwarz use triplet matching and two sensitivity parameters for internal and external bias to combine randomized and non-randomized studies; they do not characterize the observed-law support-clipped region admitting one common latent causal extension. Parikh et al. study attribution between external-validity and ignorability failures but not a simultaneous feasible extension. Chernozhukov, Lee, and Rosen inform contact selection; Masten and Poirier inform frontier inversion; Fang and Santos provide directional inference; Hong and Li provide finite-difference numerical-delta resampling; Chernozhukov et al. provide cross-fitting; and Luedtke and van der Laan explain the nonregular role of positive-mass ties. These works inform rather than establish Open-ended Question 2.",
  "technical_internal_limitation": "The model has two studies, binary treatment, and known positive bounded outcome support. Additive sensitivity scales, zero outcomes, continuous treatments, and multi-study extensions are outside scope.",
  "honest_scope": "The mixture identity, positive-violation infeasibility implication, cancellation calculation, and zero-sensitivity algebra are proposed supporting results. Conjecture 1 remains open in its sufficiency direction: a zero conditional-violation law must be completed into one joint latent extension. Uniform tie-inclusive coverage, testing, and local separation also remain open; no margin, contact-set, bootstrap-validity, or regularity condition encodes their answer."
}
